# Golden Reference — What a Perfect Wiki Looks Like

> **Read this file ONCE before Phase 11 generates documentation.** It defines the shape,
> structure, and quality bar. Your output must match this skeleton. If it doesn't, fix it
> before writing to disk.

## A. Annotated Skeleton

The golden example is `DWH_dbo.Dim_Mirror` (313 lines, quality 9.0/10, 19 Tier 1 + 7 Tier 2).
Below is the condensed structural skeleton with annotations. Your output MUST match this shape.

```markdown
# {Schema}.{ObjectName}                          ← FULL qualified name

> {1-2 sentence summary with row count, date range, what it tracks, production source, refresh status}
                                                  ← The summary is NOT filler — it has specifics

| Property | Value |                              ← Property table: 10+ rows minimum
|----------|-------|
| **Schema** | {Schema} |
| **Object Type** | Table |
| **Production Source** | {source with SP name} |  ← Specific, not vague
| **Refresh** | {frequency + pattern} |
| **Synapse Distribution** | {HASH(col) / ROUND_ROBIN / REPLICATE} |
| **Synapse Index** | {index details} |
| **UC Target** | `{fully.qualified.uc.name}` |
| **UC Format** | delta |
| **UC Partitioned By** | {partition or None} |
| **UC Table Type** | {Gold export details} |

---

## 1. Business Meaning                           ← WHAT this table is, WHY it exists
                                                  ← Must include: row count, date range, distribution of key types
                                                  ← Must name the ETL SP and describe the load pattern
                                                  ← Must explain sentinel values (e.g., 1900-01-01 = open)

---

## 2. Business Logic                             ← Numbered subsections (2.1, 2.2, ...)

### 2.1 {Pattern Name}                           ← Each subsection follows What/Columns/Rules structure

**What**: {one sentence}
**Columns Involved**: {list}
**Rules**:
- {bullet per rule with specific values}

---

## 3. Query Advisory                             ← How to query this table efficiently

### 3.1 Synapse Distribution & Index             ← Distribution key + index implications
### 3.2 Common Query Patterns                    ← Table: Analyst Question | Recommended Approach
### 3.3 Common JOINs                             ← Table: Join To | Join Condition | Purpose
### 3.4 Gotchas                                  ← Bullet list of traps (sentinels, typos, NULL quirks)

---

## 4. Elements                                   ← THE CORE — every column documented

### Confidence Tier Legend                        ← Tier legend table (always present)

| # | Element | Type | Nullable | Description |  ← 5-column table, EVERY column, NO exceptions
                                                  ← Description MUST end with (Tier N — source)
                                                  ← Dictionary values inline if <=15 distinct (see Section C)

---

## 5. Lineage

### 5.1 Production Sources                       ← Table: Synapse Column | Production Source | Source Column | Transform
### 5.2 ETL Pipeline                             ← ASCII diagram showing the full chain:
                                                  ← Production → Lake → Staging → SP → Target → UC Gold

---

## 6. Relationships

### 6.1 References To (this object points to)    ← Table: Element | Related Object | Description
### 6.2 Referenced By (other objects point to this)

---

## 7. Sample Queries                             ← 2-3 real SQL queries analysts would run
                                                  ← Each with a descriptive ### heading

---

## 8. Atlassian Knowledge Sources                ← Confluence/Jira links OR "No sources found"

---

*Generated: {date} | Quality: {N}/10 | Phases: {N}/14*
*Tiers: {N} T1, {N} T2, {N} T3, {N} T4, {N} T5 | Elements: {N}/{N}, Logic: {N}/10, ...*
*Object: {Schema}.{ObjectName} | Type: {type} | Production Source: {source}*
```

## B. Quality Assertions — Machine-Checkable

After writing, verify EVERY assertion before saving:

| # | Assertion | How to Check | Hard/Soft |
|---|-----------|-------------|-----------|
| 1 | All 8 `## N.` sections present (1 through 8) | Count `## 1.` through `## 8.` headers | HARD |
| 2 | Every Element description ends with `(Tier N — source)` | Grep for `\(Tier [1-5] —` in Section 4 | HARD |
| 3 | Element table has 5 columns: `# \| Element \| Type \| Nullable \| Description` | Check header row | HARD |
| 4 | Element count matches DDL column count | Compare `| {N} |` max row number vs Phase 1 column count | HARD |
| 5 | Section 2 has numbered subsections with What/Columns/Rules | Check for `### 2.N` and bold `**What**:` | SOFT |
| 6 | Section 3 has a Gotchas subsection | Check for `### 3.4 Gotchas` or similar | SOFT |
| 7 | Section 5.2 has ETL pipeline ASCII diagram | Check for code block with `→` or `\|--` | HARD |
| 8 | Footer has tier breakdown counts | Check for `*Tiers:` line | HARD |
| 9 | Property table has Production Source, Refresh, Distribution, UC Target | Check for these rows | HARD |
| 10 | Summary line has row count and date range (not vague) | Check `>` line for numbers/dates | SOFT |
| 11 | Dictionary columns with <=15 values have inline values | See Section C rule | SOFT |
| 12 | `.review-needed.md` does NOT contain `## 4. Elements` | If it does, content is in the WRONG file | HARD |
| 13 | `.lineage.md` exists and was written BEFORE `.md` | Check file existence | HARD |

**If ANY HARD assertion fails: delete the file and regenerate. Do not patch.**

## C. Dictionary Inline Values Rule

When a column references a dictionary/lookup table:

| Dictionary Size | Rule | Example |
|----------------|------|---------|
| **<=15 distinct values** | Inline key=value pairs in the description | `1=Regular, 2=CopyMe, 3=Social Index, 4=Fund (Dictionary.MirrorType)` |
| **>15 distinct values** | Name the join target only, describe what it represents | `FK to Dim_Country. Resolves to country name.` |

**Threshold rationale**: 15 values fit in ~200 characters. Beyond that, inline enumeration hurts readability and adds noise.

**Naming convention awareness**: When the production Dictionary name differs from the DWH Dim name, document BOTH:
- Production: `Dictionary.MirrorType` (for lineage traceability)
- DWH: `Dim_MirrorType` (for query use)

Example from Dim_Mirror:
```
| 10 | MirrorTypeID | int | YES | 1=Regular, 2=CopyMe, 3=Social Index, 4=Fund (Dictionary.MirrorType). Determines mirror behavior. (Tier 1 — Trade.Mirror) |
```

## C2. Tier 2 Source Convention — Upstream TABLE, Not the SP

The source after `(Tier 2 — …)` names the **upstream table the transform reads from**, NOT the SP that performs the transform. This mirrors the Tier 1 convention: the source is always the data origin, never the loader.

| Column situation | RIGHT | WRONG |
|---|---|---|
| Passthrough from DWH fact, no production wiki | `(Tier 2 — Fact_Deposit_State)` | `(Tier 2 — SP_DepositWithdrawFee)` |
| ABS / sign correction on a fact column | `(Tier 2 — Fact_Deposit_State)` | `(Tier 2 — SP_DepositWithdrawFee)` |
| CASE/IF on a fact column | `(Tier 2 — Fact_BillingDeposit)` | `(Tier 2 — SP_BI_DB_Deposits)` |
| Multi-source UNION ALL | `(Tier 2 — Fact_Deposit_State / Fact_Cashout_State)` | `(Tier 2 — SP_DepositWithdrawFee)` |
| GETDATE() / @StartDateID / literal — no input column at all | `(Tier 2 — SP_DepositWithdrawFee)` | n/a — SP is correct here |

The only case where an SP name belongs in the source is when the column is purely synthesized inside the SP with NO input table column. For everything else, name the upstream table.

Example for a Tier 2 ETL-computed column:
```
| 11 | Amount | numeric(38,8) | YES | Trade amount in deposit currency. ABS() then signed via #amountDirections post-INSERT. (Tier 2 — Fact_Deposit_State) |
```

## D. Anti-Patterns — What Drift Looks Like

These are concrete examples of BAD output observed in actual production runs. If your output matches any of these, STOP and fix.

### D1. Missing Tier Suffix

```
WRONG: | 2 | CID | int | NO | Customer ID |
RIGHT: | 2 | CID | int | NO | Copier customer ID. The user who allocates money to follow the leader. (Tier 1 — Trade.Mirror) |
```

The tier suffix `(Tier N — source)` is not optional. It is written verbatim to Unity Catalog by Phase 11W. Every single element description must end with it.

### D2. Vague Business Meaning (Section 1)

```
WRONG: > This table stores mirror data for the DWH.
RIGHT: > 11.1M-row copy-trading relationship dimension table tracking every CopyTrader,
       > CopyMe (Popular Investor), Smart Portfolio, and Fund mirror relationship from
       > 2011 to present -- capturing the copier (CID), the copied person (ParentCID),
       > investment amount, open/close dates, risk settings, and financial performance.
```

Section 1 must have: row count, date range, specific business entities, ETL pattern.

### D3. Wrong File — Wiki Content in Sidecar

```
WRONG: Writing the Elements table into {ObjectName}.review-needed.md
RIGHT: The .md file gets the full 8-section wiki. The .review-needed.md gets ONLY
       Tier 4 items, questions for reviewers, and correction notes. It is a lightweight
       checklist, NOT a duplicate wiki.
```

If you find yourself writing `## 4. Elements` into `.review-needed.md`, you are writing to the WRONG file. Stop and redirect to `.md`.

### D4. Elements Table Missing Columns

```
WRONG: | # | Element | Description |              ← Only 3 columns, missing Type and Nullable
RIGHT: | # | Element | Type | Nullable | Description |  ← All 5 columns required
```

### D5. ETL Pipeline Without Detail

```
WRONG: ## 5. Lineage
       Data comes from production via ETL.

RIGHT: ## 5. Lineage
       ### 5.2 ETL Pipeline
       ```
       etoro.Trade.Mirror (active, etoroDB-REAL)
         |-- Generic Pipeline (Bronze export) ---|
         v
       DWH_staging.etoro_Trade_Mirror
         |-- SP_Dim_Mirror_DL_To_Synapse @dt ---|
         v
       DWH_dbo.Dim_Mirror (11.1M rows)
         |-- Generic Pipeline (Override, delta) ---|
         v
       dwh.gold_sql_dp_prod_we_dwh_dbo_dim_mirror
       ```
```

The ETL pipeline must be a concrete ASCII diagram with table names, SP names, and row counts.
